<p class="eyebrow">Contact</p>
<h1>Route the request to the team that can actually solve it.</h1>
<p class="lede">Use separate contact paths for sales, technical support, billing, porting, partnerships, legal, and press so the first response starts with context instead of triage.</p>
<p class="hero-actions">
	<a class="btn btn-primary" href="mailto:support@voicetel.com">Email support</a>
	<a class="btn btn-secondary" href="https://www.voicetel.com">Sign in</a>
</p>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="contact-grid">
	<h2>Contact paths</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Sales</strong> — Pricing reviews, migrations, volume modeling, SIP trunking, hosted PBX, messaging, and procurement questions.</li>
		<li><strong>Support</strong> — Call failures, SIP traces, webhook errors, number routing, messaging delivery, app access, and SDN connectivity.</li>
		<li><strong>Billing</strong> — Invoices, rate questions, credits, payment method issues, and account-level billing changes.</li>
		<li><strong>Porting</strong> — Number inventory, LOA, losing-carrier data, rejection resolution, scheduling, and cutover coordination.</li>
		<li><strong>Partnerships</strong> — Carrier, reseller, platform, integration, and channel opportunities.</li>
		<li><strong>Press and legal</strong> — Media requests, legal notices, policy questions, and compliance routing.</li>
	</ul>
</section>

<section class="section-block" data-section-type="form-copy">
	<h2>Form copy</h2>
	<p>For account-specific issues, ask customers to sign in so VoiceTel can attach account, service, and ticket context automatically. For non-account requests, route by topic.</p>
</section>
